value.value: A group of cells in the vicinity of the superior olivary complex in the pontine tegmentum that label for norepinephine in primates, rodents, and other mammals.
A group of cells fluorescent for norepinephrine that is located in the pontine reticular formation ventral to the superior cerebellar peduncle of the pons in rodents and in primates.
A group of cells fluorescent for norepinephrine that are scattered in the nucleus subceruleus of the macaque.

A group of cells fluorescent for norepinephrine that are located in the central gray of the midbrain at the level of the trochlear nucleus in the squirrel monkey (Saimiri) and to a lesser degree in the macaque.
A cortical area between the agranular insular cortex and the supplemental somatosensory area in rats and mice. The VISC is the architectonically equivalent structure granular insula in humans.
A small group of cells located lateral to the pyramid of the medulla in the rat and the mouse that functionally it belongs to the reticular formation of the subcortical motor system.
The part of the parapyramidal nucleus that is closely adjacent to the inner surface of the pyramidal tract.
The part of the parapyramidal nucleus that is located on the ventral surface of the medulla lateral to the pyramidal tract.

A group of neurons in the floor of the fourth ventricle, in close proximity to the nucleus of the hypoglossal nerve in the gray substance of the medulla oblongata, all of which contain cells with characteristics suggestive of reticular connections.

Nerve fibers that originate in the magnocellular red nucleus, cross to the other side of the midbrain, and descend in the lateral part of the brainstem tegmentum in the midbrain, and travel through the lateral funiculus of the spinal cord, coursing adjacent to the lateral corticospinal tract.

A part of the striatum which is primarilly composed of amygdalar areas. The sAMY is composed of the anterior amygdalar area, central amygdalar nucleus, intercalated amygdalar nucleus, medial amygdalar nucleus, and the bed nucleus of the accessory olfactory tract.

The main route taken by fibers from the ventral subiculum to the hypothalamus, where they innervate the medial preoptic area, “shell” of the ventromedial nucleus, dorsomedial nucleus, ventral premammillary  nucleus, and cell-poor zone around the medial mammillary nucleus.
A region in the medial prefrontal cortex that is dorsal to the infralimbic area important in expression of conditioned reward and fear behaviour.
A region in the medial prefrontal cortex that is ventral to the prelimbic area important in supression of conditioned reward and fear behaviour.
A subdivision of inferior cerebellar peduncle that connects the medulla to the cerebellum.
A region in the dorsal pons that plays a central role in inducing motor suppression during REM sleep.
A premotoneuron pool in the trigeminal reflex arc that is a key structure of jaw movement control.
A small cluster of neurons dorsal to the facial motor nucleus in the pontine tegmentum.
A small region of neurons in the brainstem, dorsolateral to the genu of facial nerve, that have efferents to the vestibular periphery.
The cortical region between the cortical amygdalar area and the piriform area.
In the human and macaque, the piriform-amygdalar area is not distinguished from the postpiriform transition area.
A cytoarchitectonic area on the medial surface of the cerebral hemisphere rostral to the septum, ventral to the infralimbic area and dorsal to the tenia tecta in the mouse and rat.
Some authors regard it not as a separate structure but as the ventral part of the infralimbic area.
A hypothalamic region in rodents that is homologous to the lateral tuberal nucleus in humans and higher primates and is involved in energy homeostasis.

While lateral tuberal nucleus is often used interchangeably with tuberal nucleus in rodents, lateral tuberal nucleus is specific to humans and higher primates. In some cases, lateral tuberal nucleus is thought to be part of the tuberal nucleus in rodents, and could possibly be homologous to human tuberal region instead.
A prominent nucleus located in the ventral tuberal area of Teleostei that is anatomically homologous to the hypothalamic arcuate (infundibular)-median eminence (ME) system of tetrpods.

This term is used specifically for fish (or Teleostei in general) as lateral tuberal nucleus (UBERON:0000435) refers to a structure that is specific to humans and higher primates. See https://github.com/obophenotype/uberon/issues/2439 for more details.
A structure embedded in the superior olivary complex that is driven by input pathways from the octopus cells in the cochlear nucleus and the neurons of the medial nucleus of the trapezoid body.
A laminar subdivision of the neocortex that is comprised of the more surface layers, commonly layers two through four.

label.value: second visual cortical area (sensu Mustela putorius furo)

value.value: A visual area in the ferret that is rostral to area 17, caudal to area 19 and also abuts PPc and area 20a.

label.value: third visual cortical area (sensu Mustela putorius furo)

value.value: A visual area in the ferret located rostral to area 18 and caudal to area 21.

label.value: fourth visual cortical area (sensu Mustela putorius furo)

value.value: A visual area in the ferret that is caudal to the suprasylvian visual areas and rostral to area 19.

label.value: temporal visual area a (sensu Mustela putorius furo)

value.value: A visual area in the ferret that is posterior to area 20b and lies lateral to areas 17, 18, and 19.

label.value: temporal visual area b (sensu Mustela putorius furo)

value.value: A visual area in the ferret that is posterior to area PS and anterior to 20a.

label.value: posterior parietal rostral cortical area (sensu Mustela putorius furo)

value.value: A multimodal area of the ferret involved in vision and somatosensation that lies between the medial wall of the hemisphere and the medial lip of the suprasylvian sulcus and is posterior to caudal somatosensory cortex (SIII) and anterior to PPc.
A laminar subdivision of the neocortex that is comprised of the deeper layers, commonly layers five and six, however, could also consist part of layer four.

label.value: posterior parietal caudal cortical area (sensu Mustela putorius furo)

value.value: A visual area in the ferret that  lies between the medial wall of the hemisphere and the medial lip of the suprasylvian sulcus and is posterior to PPr and anterior to area 18 (on the lateral gyrus) and area 21 (on the suprasylvian gyrus).

label.value: anteromedial lateral suprasylvian visual area (sensu Mustela putorius furo)

value.value: A visual area in the ferret that lies medial to the fundus in the suprasylvian sulcus, posterior to the MRSS and anterior to the PMLS.

label.value: anterolateral lateral suprasylvian visual area (sensu Mustela putorius furo)

value.value: A visual area in the ferret that lies on the lateral bank of the suprasylvian sulcus, posterior to SIII, anterior to area PLLS and medial to A1.

label.value: posteromedial lateral suprasylvian visual area (sensu Mustela putorius furo)

value.value: A visual area in the ferret that is located in the posterior bank of the suprasylvian sulcus.

label.value: posterolateral lateral suprasylvian visual area (sensu Mustela putorius furo)

value.value: A visual area in the ferret located in the lateral bank of the suprasylvian sulcus posterior to ALLS, anteriomedial to DLS and lateral to PMLS.

label.value: dorsal lateral suprasylvian visual cortical area (sensu Mustela putorius furo)

value.value: A visual area in the ferret located in the lateral bank of the suprasylvian sulcus anterior to VLS and posterior to PLLS.

label.value: ventral lateral suprasylvian visual area (sensu Mustela putorius furo)

value.value: A visual area in the ferret located in the medial bank of the suprasylvian sulvus lateral to area PMLS.

label.value: posterior suprasylvian visual cortical area (sensu Mustela putorius furo)

value.value: A visual area in the ferret that is lateral to the occipital visual areas (area 17, 18, 19 and 21), medial to perirhinal cortex and anterior to area 20b.

label.value: anterior ectosylvian visual area (sensu Mustela putorius furo)

value.value: A multimodal area in the ferret responsive to visual, somatic, and auditory stimuli. The anterior border of AEV is coincident with the anterior portion of the ectosylvian gyrus containing higher order somatosensory cortical areas and the posterior border abuts higher order auditory cortical areas.

label.value: spenial visual area (sensu Mustela putorius furo)

value.value: A visual area in the ferret located on the dorsal bank of the splenial sulcus between the medial border of area 17 and the lateral borter of CVA.

label.value: cingulate visual area (sensu Mustela putorius furo)

value.value: A visual area of the ferret located in the fundus of the splenial sulcus medial to SVA.

label.value: A lamina of the lateral geniculate nucleus (sensu Mustela putorius furo)

value.value: A major laminae of the lateral geniculate nucleus of the ferret receiving crossed retinal inputs, located medial to the C laminae and lateral to the A1 and P laminae.

label.value: A1 lamina of the lateral geniculate nucleus (sensu Mustela putorius furo)

value.value: A major laminae of the lateral geniculate nucleus of the ferret receiving uncrossed retinal inputs, located medial to the C and A laminae (Linden, Guillery & Cucchiaro, 1981)

label.value: C lamina of the lateral geniculate nucleus (sensu Mustela putorius furo)

value.value: The most lateral laminae of the LGN of the ferret. The C laminae includes the C lamina, which is the innermost layer, followed by C1, C2, and C3 being the outermost lamina.

label.value: Perigeniculate lamina of the lateral geniculate nucleus (sensu Mustela putorius furo)

value.value: A lamina of the LGN in the ferret located medial to the A lamina in the rostral regions of the visual thalamus ((Linden, Guillery & Cucchiaro, 1981; Dell, Innocenti, Hilgetag, & Manger, 2019).

A nucleus of the brain that is embedded in the pontine tegmentum, it is defined on the basis of inputs from the lateral hypothalamic area and central amygdalar nucleus, it is located ventral to the locus ceruleus, dorsal to Barrington's nucleus, lateral to the laterodorsal tegmental nucleus, and medial to the midbrain trigeminal nucleus.

A nucleus of the brain that is the most ventral portion of the gigantocellular nucleus in the medullary reticular formation, between the lateral paragigantocellular nucleus and the midline or nucleus raphe magnus. Functionally it belongs to the reticular formation (functional) of the subcortical motor system.

label.value: interstitial nucleus of the vestibular nerve

value.value: A cluster of large nerve cells distributed in the vestibular component of vestibulocochlear nerve fibers that functionally belong to the vestibulomotor regions of the behavioral control column.
Interstitial nucleus of the vestibular nerve is revealed in Nissl stained sections and stain for acetylcholinesterase.
